  \subsection{Three families of constants} % (fold)
  \label{sec:three_families_of_constants}

We have nearly gotten to the bottom of $\pi$. To complete the excavation, we'll need general formulas for the surface area and volume of an $n$-sphere. To derive them, we'll proceed inductively using the formulas from Section~\ref{sec:volume_of_a_hypersphere}. (An alternate method is discussed in an appendix (Section~\ref{sec:untangling_the_hypersphere}).)
 
 We'll start with the examples in Table~\ref{table:n_sphere_volumes}. We see that the denominators consist of products of numbers such as $1\cdot3\cdot5$ and $2\cdot4\cdot6$. Since we built up these formulas recursively, this ascending order was more natural for our purposes, but of course using commutativity we can rearrange them in descending order as follows: $5\cdot3\cdot1$ and $6\cdot4\cdot2$. Written this way, we see that the products bear a strong resemblance to the \emph{factorial function}:
\[ 
n! = n(n-1)(n-2)\ldots 2\cdot 1.
\]
The difference here is that each successive term differs by $2$ instead of by $1$. The resulting function, called the \emph{double factorial function}, is uncommon but elementary:
\[ n!! = \begin{cases}
 n(n-2)(n-4)\ldots6\cdot4\cdot2 & \text{if } n \text{ is even}; \\ \\
 n(n-2)(n-4)\ldots5\cdot3\cdot1 & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
 \end{cases} \]
Inspecting Table~\ref{table:n_sphere_volumes} closely shows that the surface area formulas contain factors of $(n-2)!!$, while the volume formulas contain $n!!$.

We also notice from Table~\ref{table:n_sphere_volumes} that the factors of $\tau$ increase every \emph{two} dimensions, so that the even and odd formulas on each row have the same power of $\tau$. In particular, we have a factor of $\tau^{n/2}$ when $n$ is even and $\tau^{(n-1)/2}$ when $n$ is odd. We can unify these formulas using the \emph{floor function} $\lfloor x \rfloor$, which is simply the largest integer less than or equal to $x$ (so that, e.g., $\lfloor 3.7 \rfloor = \lfloor 3.2 \rfloor = 3$). With this, we see that each formula has a factor of~$\tau^{\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor}$. For example, when $n=4$ we have $\tau^{\lfloor\frac{4}{2}\rfloor} = \tau^{\lfloor2\rfloor} = \tau^2$, and when $n=5$ we have $\tau^{\lfloor\frac{5}{2}\rfloor} = \tau^{\lfloor2+1/2\rfloor} = \tau^2$, yielding the same power of~$\tau$.

Putting everything together, we have the following general formulas:
\[ S_n = \frac{\tau^{\left\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \right\rfloor}\,r^{n-1}}{(n-2)!!}\times \begin{cases}
 1 & \text{if } n \text{ is even}; \\ \\
 2 & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
 \end{cases} \]
 and
\[ V_n = \frac{\tau^{\left\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \right\rfloor}\,r^n}{n!!}\times \begin{cases}
 1 & \text{if } n \text{ is even}; \\ \\
 2 & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
 \end{cases} \]
 (See the appendix in Section~\ref{sec:untangling_the_hypersphere} to see how much better these expressions are than the ones found in standard references.) We see from these formulas that the surface area and volume formulas define two \emph{families} of constants, which we'll call $\tau_n$ and $\sigma_n$:
\[
\tau_n \equiv \frac{S_n}{r^{n-1}} = \frac{\tau^{\left\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \right\rfloor}}{(n-2)!!}\times \begin{cases}
 1 & \text{if } n \text{ is even}; \\ \\
 2 & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
 \end{cases}
\]
and 
\[
\sigma_n \equiv \frac{V_n}{r^n} = \frac{\tau^{\left\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \right\rfloor}}{n!!}\times \begin{cases}
 1 & \text{if } n \text{ is even}; \\ \\
 2 & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
 \end{cases}
\]
%(Note that $\tau_2 = S_2/r^{2-1} = \tau^{1/1}/(2-2)!! = \tau$. This is a consistency check, not a coincidence, because $\tau = S_2/r$ by definition.) 
With these families of constants, we can write the surface area and volume formulas compactly as follows:
\[ S_n = \tau_n\,r^{n-1} \]
and
\[ V_n = \sigma_n\,r^n. \]
Because of the relation $V_n = \int S_n\,dr$, we have the simple relationship
\[
\sigma_n = \frac{\tau_n}{n}.
\]
You can verify by plugging in different values of $n$ that these surface area and volume formulas reproduce the values shown in Table~\ref{table:n_sphere_volumes}.

Let us make some observations about these two families of constants. The first and most important observation is that $\tau$ is the only constant common to every member of the two families. To understand the family $\tau_n$, we can set $r=1$ to see that each $\tau_n$ is the surface area of a unit $n$-sphere, which is also the angle measure of a full $n$-sphere. In particular, by writing $s_n$ as the $n$-dimensional ``arclength'' equal to a fraction~$f$ of the full surface area~$S_n$, we have
\[
\theta_n \equiv \frac{s_n}{r^{n-1}} = \frac{f S_n}{r^{n-1}} = f\left(\frac{S_n}{r^{n-1}}\right) = f\tau_n.
\]
Here $\theta_n$ is simply the $n$-dimensional generalization of radian angle measure, and we see that $\tau_n$ is the generalization of ``one turn'' to $n$ dimensions, which explains why $\tau_2 = \tau$ leads naturally to the diagram shown in Figure~\ref{fig:tau_angles}.

Meanwhile, the $\sigma_n$ are the volumes of unit $n$-spheres. In particular, $\sigma_2$ is the area of a unit disk:
\[
\sigma_2 = \frac{\tau_2}{2} = \frac{\tau}{2}.
\]
This shows that $\sigma_2 = \tau/2 = 3.14159\ldots$ does have an independent geometric significance. Note, however, that not only does $\sigma_2$ ultimately derive its value from $\tau$, \emph{it has nothing to do with circumferences or diameters}. In other words, \emph{$\pi = C/D$ is not a member of the family~$\sigma_n$}.

So, to which family of constants does $\pi$ naturally belong?
Let's rewrite $\pi = C/D$ in terms more appropriate for generalization to higher dimensions:
\[
\pi = \frac{C}{D} = \frac{S_2}{D^{2-1}}.
\]
We thus see that $\pi$ is naturally associated with surface areas divided by the power of the diameter necessary to yield a dimensionless constant.
This suggests introducing a third family of constants~$\pi_n$:
\[
\pi_n \equiv \frac{S_n}{D^{n-1}}.
\]
We can express this family in terms of the $\tau_n$ as follows:
\[
\pi_n = \frac{S_n}{D^{n-1}} = \frac{S_n}{(2r)^{n-1}} = 
\frac{S_n}{2^{n-1}r^{n-1}} = \frac{\tau_n}{2^{n-1}}.
\]

We are now finally in a position to understand exactly what is wrong with $\pi$. The principal geometric significance of $3.14159\ldots$ is that it is the area of a unit disk. But this number comes from evaluating $\sigma_n = \tau_n/n$ when $n=2$:
\[
\sigma_2 = \frac{\tau_2}{2} = \frac{\tau}{2}.
\]
It's true that this equals $\pi_2$:
\[
\pi_2 = \pi = \frac{\tau_2}{2^{2-1}} = \frac{\tau}{2}.
\]
But this equality is a coincidence: it occurs only because $2^{n-1}$ happens to equal $n$ when $n=2$. In all higher dimensions, $n$ and $2^{n-1}$ are distinct. In other words, \emph{the geometric significance of $\pi$ is the result of a mathematical pun}.

As seen clearly in Table~\ref{table:n_sphere_volumes_pi_D}, there is no earthly reason why you would want to divide $S_n$ by $D^{n-1}$. An $n$-sphere is defined by its \emph{radius}, not by its diameter. The $\pi_n$ family of constants, including $\pi$ itself, has no particular geometric significance whatsoever.
  
  % subsection three_families_of_constants (end)

  \subsection{What is really going on here?} % (fold)
  \label{sec:what_is_really_going_on}

Even after reading this manifesto, you might be tempted by the thought that the difference between $\pi$ and $\tau$ isn't really that important after all. You may find yourself saying, ``Both numbers are important: sometimes $\pi$ is better, sometimes $\tau$ is more natural, and sometimes they are equally good.'' For example, consider the famous \href{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leibniz_formula_for_pi}{Leibniz series} for $\pi$: \[ \frac{\pi}{4} = 1 - 1/3 + 1/5 - 1/7 + \cdots \] Is it really any better to write \[ \frac{\tau}{8} = 1 - 1/3 + 1/5 - 1/7 + \cdots \] instead? 

As in previous examples, we could make a \emph{specific} argument for $\tau$, in this case by noting that the Leibniz series is simply the \href{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_trigonometric_functions#Infinite_series}{infinite series for  $\arctan x$} evaluated at $x=1$, which is the angle where sine and cosine are equal, which is an eighth of a turn, which is $\tau/8$. This same issue afflicts many arguments in the Pi Manifesto, which includes formulas such as elliptical area ($\pi a b$, which comes from integrating an elliptical function from $0$ to $2\pi$) and integrals such as
\[ 
\int_{-1}^1 \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\,dx = \pi,
\]
which evaluates to $\sin^{-1}(1) - \sin^{-1}(-1)$, i.e., the difference between where $\sin\theta$ is $1$ (a quarter turn) and $-1$ (a negative quarter turn): $\tau/4 - (-\tau/4) = \tau/2$. \href{http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/und_so_weiter}{\emph{Und so weiter}}. 

Fortunately, there is no need to do this case-by-case refutation of $\pi$: we saw in Section~\ref{sec:volume_of_a_hypersphere} that all occurrences of $\pi$ ultimately trace to the equation
\[
C = 2\pi r,
\]
which is unambiguously simpler in terms of $\tau$:\footnote{This addresses an issue raised by computer \href{http://www.catb.org/~esr/faqs/hacker-howto.html}{hacker} and mathematical philosopher Eric Raymond in his post \href{http://esr.ibiblio.org/?p=3481}{Tau versus Pi}. He suggests the following contest: ``Representatives of the Tauists and the pi partisans should be locked in a mathematics library until they choose a list of books and papers that covers trigonometry, calculus, and analysis. Then, the burden should be on the Tauists to translate the entire pile into $\tau$ notation. Then, both sides should count symbols, checking each others' work. Most compact notation wins!'' Such an audit is unnecessary, because all occurrences of $\pi$ ultimately derive from $C = 2\pi r$. We need only compare that equation with $C = \tau\,r$, and there is no doubt about which one uses fewer symbols.}
\[
C = \tau\,r.
\]
It makes no more sense to have a separate symbol for $\tau/2$ than it does to have a separate symbol for $1/2$. Indeed, imagine we lived in a world where we used the letter $h$ to represent ``one half'' and had no separate notation for $2h$. We would then observe that $h$ is ubiquitous in mathematics. In fact, $2h$ is the \href{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_element}{multiplicative identity}, so how can one doubt the importance of $h$? But this is crazy: $2h$ is the fundamental number, not $h$. Let us therefore introduce a separate symbol for $2h$; call it $1$. We then see that $h = 1/2$, and there is no longer any reason to use $h$ at all. 

This hypothetical scenario becomes reality in the case of circles: what is really going on here is that \emph{$\pi$ is half of something}. We have a standard symbol ($\pi$) for half a ``circular unit'', but we have no standard symbol for the unit itself. Whether we use $\tau$ or some other symbol, \emph{the circular unit needs a name}. If you ever hear yourself saying things like, ``Sometimes $\pi$ is the best choice, and sometimes it's $2\pi$'', stop and remember the words of \href{http://vihart.com/}{Vi Hart} in her wonderful \href{http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jG7vhMMXagQ}{video about tau}: ``No! You're making excuses for $\pi$.'' It's time to stop making excuses.

